  "prompt": "I feel lost and I have lost faith in Islam, but not in God. Any advice or books I can read?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry to hear that you're feeling this way. Navigating questions about faith can be challenging, but seeking understanding and clarity is a courageous step. Here are some suggestions that might help you on your journey:\n\n### Books to Consider:\n\n1. **\"The Road to Mecca\" by Muhammad Asad**\n   - An autobiography of a man who embraced Islam later in life, offering personal insights and reflections on faith.\n\n2. **\"Mistaken Identity: A Return to the Genuine Message of Islam\" by Ali Ataie**\n   - Explores the core principles of Islam and addresses common misconceptions, potentially offering a fresh perspective.\n\n3. **\"The Heart of the Qur'an: An Introduction to Islamic Spirituality\" by Lex Hixon**\n   - Delves into the spiritual teachings of the Qur'an, focusing on personal growth and inner peace.\n\n4. **\"Islam and the Future of Tolerance: A Dialogue\" by Sam Harris and Maajid Nawaz**\n   - A thoughtful conversation between a former Islamist and a critic of Islam, exploring ways to bridge understanding and promote change.\n\n5. **\"When Bad Things Happen to Good People\" by Harold S. Kushner**\n   - While not specifically about Islam, this book addresses questions of faith and suffering, which might resonate with your current feelings.\n\n### Additional Advice:\n\n- **Seek Conversations:** Engaging in open and honest dialogues with trusted friends, family members, or faith leaders can provide support and different perspectives.\n  \n- **Join Support Groups:** There are communities and support groups, both online and offline, for individuals exploring their faith or questioning religious beliefs.\n\n- **Reflect Through Journaling:** Writing down your thoughts and feelings can help clarify your emotions and the reasons behind your current perspective.\n\n- **Consider Professional Guidance:** Speaking with a counselor or therapist who is experienced in spiritual or religious matters can offer personalized support.\n\nRemember, it's okay to question and seek your own path. Faith journeys are deeply personal, and taking the time to explore your beliefs can lead to greater understanding and peace.",
